FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h11i-01-1 — Kaiser's Germany 1890–1918
  {id:"h11fc-01-1-1", islandId:"h11i-01-1", front:"What was the political structure of Kaiser Wilhelm II's Germany?",
   back:"Germany was ruled under the constitution of the Second Reich (1871):\n\n• The Kaiser — head of state with power to appoint and dismiss the Chancellor, control foreign policy and command the armed forces.\n• The Chancellor — head of government, answerable only to the Kaiser, not to parliament.\n• The Reichstag — elected parliament that could debate and vote on laws, but could not remove the Chancellor.\n• The Bundesrat — federal council representing the 25 German states.\n\nIn practice, the Kaiser held autocratic power. The Reichstag could block budgets but had limited real influence.", difficulty:1, category:"definition"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-1-2", islandId:"h11i-01-1", front:"How did industrialisation change Germany by 1914?",
   back:"Germany underwent rapid industrialisation in the late 19th century:\n\n• By 1914 it was the largest industrial economy in Europe, overtaking Britain in steel and chemical production.\n• Urbanisation — millions moved to cities, creating a large industrial working class.\n• The Social Democratic Party (SPD) grew rapidly, winning the most Reichstag seats by 1912.\n• Working-class demands for better conditions and political representation threatened the conservative elite.\n\nThe Kaiser and Junker (landowning) class feared socialist revolution and used nationalism and militarism to distract from domestic tensions.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-1-3", islandId:"h11i-01-1", front:"Why did Germany lose the First World War?",
   back:"Several factors contributed to Germany's defeat:\n\n• The British naval blockade caused severe food shortages — the 'Turnip Winter' of 1916–17 led to malnutrition and civilian unrest.\n• The failure of the Spring Offensive (March 1918) exhausted Germany's last reserves.\n• The entry of the USA in April 1917 brought fresh troops and resources the Central Powers could not match.\n• Morale collapsed — mutinies in the navy (Kiel, October 1918) and revolution in German cities forced the Kaiser to abdicate on 9 November 1918.\n\nThe armistice was signed on 11 November 1918.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-1-4", islandId:"h11i-01-1", front:"What was Weltpolitik and why was it significant?",
   back:"Weltpolitik ('world policy') was Kaiser Wilhelm II's aggressive foreign policy aiming to make Germany a global power.\n\nKey elements:\n• Building a large navy to rival Britain's Royal Navy (Naval Laws of 1898 and 1900).\n• Acquiring colonies in Africa and the Pacific.\n• Asserting German influence in international crises (e.g. the Moroccan Crises of 1905 and 1911).\n\nWeltpolitik increased tensions with Britain and France, contributed to the alliance system and helped create the conditions for the First World War.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-1-5", islandId:"h11i-01-1", front:"How did the First World War lead to the Kaiser's abdication?",
   back:"By late 1918, Germany faced military defeat, economic collapse and revolution:\n\n• The British blockade caused mass starvation — civilian deaths from malnutrition and disease exceeded 750,000.\n• The Spring Offensive failed, and Allied counter-attacks pushed German forces back.\n• In October 1918, sailors at Kiel mutinied rather than face a suicidal naval attack.\n• Workers' and soldiers' councils (similar to Russian soviets) formed across Germany.\n• On 9 November 1918, the Kaiser abdicated and fled to the Netherlands.\n• Friedrich Ebert (SPD) declared Germany a republic, and the armistice followed on 11 November.", difficulty:2, category:"application"}
);
