Object.assign(LESSONS, {
  "h11i-01-1": `<h2>Kaiser's Germany 1890–1918</h2>
<p>Germany under Kaiser Wilhelm II (r. 1888–1918) was an <strong>autocratic state</strong> with a democratic veneer. The Kaiser appointed the Chancellor, controlled foreign policy and commanded the military. The elected Reichstag could debate and vote on laws but could not remove the Chancellor.</p>
<p><strong>Industrialisation</strong> transformed Germany into Europe's largest industrial economy by 1914, creating a powerful working class whose political voice — the <strong>SPD</strong> — alarmed the conservative elite. The Kaiser pursued <strong>Weltpolitik</strong>, an aggressive programme of naval expansion and colonial acquisition that worsened relations with Britain and France.</p>
<p>The <strong>First World War</strong> (1914–18) brought military stalemate, the devastating British blockade and the 'Turnip Winter' of 1916–17. By October 1918, sailors mutinied at Kiel, revolution spread, and the Kaiser abdicated on 9 November. Germany became a republic.</p>
<h3>Worked example</h3>
<p><strong>Q: Explain two ways in which industrialisation created problems for the Kaiser. (8 marks)</strong></p>
<p>First, industrialisation created a large urban <strong>working class</strong> who demanded better wages, conditions and political representation. The SPD became the largest party in the Reichstag by 1912, challenging the Kaiser's autocratic system.</p>
<p>Second, rapid industrial growth fuelled <strong>militarism and Weltpolitik</strong>. Germany's expanding industries produced weapons and warships, encouraging the Kaiser to pursue aggressive foreign policies that increased tensions with Britain and France, ultimately contributing to the outbreak of war in 1914.</p>
<h3>Common mistake</h3>
<p>Students often describe the Reichstag as powerless. In fact it could block budgets and had to approve new laws — it was weak, not powerless. Examiners reward precise descriptions of its limited role.</p>`
});

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h11i-01-2 — The Weimar Republic 1918–33
  {id:"h11fc-01-2-1", islandId:"h11i-01-2", front:"What were the strengths and weaknesses of the Weimar Constitution?",
   back:"Strengths:\n• Universal suffrage — all men and women over 20 could vote.\n• Proportional representation ensured a range of views in the Reichstag.\n• The Bill of Rights guaranteed freedoms of speech, religion and assembly.\n\nWeaknesses:\n• Proportional representation led to many small parties and unstable coalition governments.\n• Article 48 allowed the President to rule by decree in an 'emergency' — this was later exploited.\n• The President could dissolve the Reichstag and call new elections.\n• The army and judiciary were largely unchanged from the Kaiser's era and often unsympathetic to democracy.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-2-2", islandId:"h11i-01-2", front:"What were the main crises facing the Weimar Republic in 1919–23?",
   back:"The Weimar Republic faced severe threats from both left and right:\n\n• Spartacist Revolt (Jan 1919) — communist uprising in Berlin, crushed by the Freikorps.\n• Kapp Putsch (March 1920) — right-wing attempt to overthrow the government, defeated by a general strike.\n• The Treaty of Versailles (June 1919) — the 'diktat' imposed war guilt, reparations and territorial losses, humiliating Germany.\n• Hyperinflation (1923) — caused by the French occupation of the Ruhr and the government printing money. Prices doubled every few days, destroying savings.\n• Munich Putsch (Nov 1923) — Hitler's failed attempt to seize power in Bavaria.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-2-3", islandId:"h11i-01-2", front:"How did Stresemann stabilise Germany 1924–29?",
   back:"Gustav Stresemann served as Chancellor (Aug–Nov 1923) and then Foreign Minister (1923–29).\n\nEconomic recovery:\n• Introduced the Rentenmark (1923) to end hyperinflation.\n• Negotiated the Dawes Plan (1924) — US loans to rebuild German industry; reparations restructured.\n• The Young Plan (1929) reduced total reparations and extended the payment period.\n\nForeign policy:\n• Locarno Pact (1925) — Germany accepted its western borders, improving relations with France.\n• Germany joined the League of Nations (1926).\n• Kellogg-Briand Pact (1928) — Germany agreed to settle disputes peacefully.\n\nThis period is often called the 'Golden Age' of Weimar, though recovery depended heavily on US loans.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-2-4", islandId:"h11i-01-2", front:"How did the Great Depression affect the Weimar Republic?",
   back:"The Wall Street Crash (October 1929) triggered the Great Depression, devastating Germany:\n\n• US loans were recalled — German banks and businesses collapsed.\n• Unemployment rose from 1.3 million (1929) to over 6 million (1933).\n• The middle class, already scarred by hyperinflation, lost faith in democracy.\n• Poverty and desperation drove voters to extremist parties.\n• The Nazi Party's vote rose from 2.6% (1928) to 37.3% (July 1932).\n• Governments ruled by presidential decree under Article 48 as coalitions failed.\n\nThe Depression created the conditions Hitler needed to come to power.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-2-5", islandId:"h11i-01-2", front:"What was the significance of Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution?",
   back:"Article 48 gave the President emergency powers to rule by decree, bypassing the Reichstag.\n\nIt was intended for genuine crises (e.g. Ebert used it over 130 times in the early Republic).\n\nHowever, it became a fatal weakness:\n• From 1930, Chancellor Brüning governed largely through Article 48 as he could not command a Reichstag majority.\n• It accustomed Germans to government without democratic debate.\n• In 1933, Hindenburg used it to appoint Hitler as Chancellor and later to pass the Reichstag Fire Decree, suspending civil liberties.\n\nArticle 48 allowed the legal destruction of Weimar democracy.", difficulty:2, category:"application"}
);
