Object.assign(LESSONS, {
  "h11i-01-3": `<h2>Nazi Rise &amp; Rule 1933–45</h2>
<p>Hitler was appointed Chancellor on 30 January 1933. Within 18 months he became <strong>Führer</strong> — absolute dictator — through a combination of legal manipulation, propaganda and terror.</p>
<p>Key steps: the <strong>Reichstag Fire Decree</strong> suspended civil liberties; the <strong>Enabling Act</strong> bypassed parliament; the <strong>Night of the Long Knives</strong> eliminated rivals; and Hindenburg's death allowed Hitler to merge the offices of President and Chancellor. The army swore a personal oath of loyalty.</p>
<p>Nazi Germany was controlled through <strong>Goebbels's propaganda machine</strong> (radio, rallies, film, censorship) and the <strong>SS and Gestapo</strong> terror apparatus. Young people were indoctrinated through the Hitler Youth and a rewritten curriculum. Jewish communities faced escalating persecution — from boycotts and the <strong>Nuremberg Laws</strong> (1935) to <strong>Kristallnacht</strong> (1938) and the <strong>Holocaust</strong> (from 1942).</p>
<h3>Worked example</h3>
<p><strong>Q: Explain two ways the Nazis controlled the German people. (8 marks)</strong></p>
<p>First, the Nazis used <strong>propaganda</strong>. Goebbels controlled all media: newspapers were censored, cheap radios broadcast Hitler's speeches into every home, and mass rallies like Nuremberg created an atmosphere of power and unity. This shaped public opinion and made opposition seem futile.</p>
<p>Second, the Nazis used <strong>terror</strong>. The SS and Gestapo arrested political opponents, trade unionists and anyone suspected of disloyalty. Concentration camps such as Dachau (opened 1933) were used to detain and intimidate. Fear of arrest silenced potential opposition.</p>
<h3>Common mistake</h3>
<p>Students often focus only on terror. In reality, many Germans genuinely supported the Nazis — unemployment fell, national pride was restored, and propaganda was highly effective. The best answers discuss both consent and coercion.</p>`
});

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h11i-01-4 — Nazi Control: The Police State & Propaganda
  {id:"h11fc-01-4-1", islandId:"h11i-01-4", front:"How did the SS and Gestapo create a Nazi police state?",
   back:"The Nazi police state was built on overlapping organisations of terror, led by Heinrich Himmler:\n\n• The SS (Schutzstaffel) — Hitler's elite, fanatically loyal force. After the Night of the Long Knives (1934) it dominated the security system, ran the concentration camps and enforced racial policy.\n• The Gestapo (secret state police) — led by Reinhard Heydrich. It spied on the population, arrested suspects without trial and relied heavily on ordinary Germans denouncing one another.\n• The SD (Sicherheitsdienst) — the intelligence-gathering arm of the SS.\n\nThe overlapping forces created a climate of fear in which most Germans assumed they were being watched.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-4-2", islandId:"h11i-01-4", front:"What were concentration camps used for in the 1930s?",
   back:"Concentration camps were a central tool of the police state:\n\n• The first camp, Dachau, opened in 1933 to hold political prisoners — communists, socialists and trade unionists.\n• Prisoners later included Jews, Roma, homosexuals, Jehovah's Witnesses and 'work-shy' people.\n• Inmates faced forced labour, brutal discipline, starvation and frequent death.\n• Camps were run by the SS 'Death's Head' units.\n\nIn the 1930s the camps were mainly for detention, punishment and intimidation. Only from 1941–42 did dedicated extermination camps emerge for the systematic murder of the Holocaust.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-4-3", islandId:"h11i-01-4", front:"How did the Nazis control the legal system and the courts?",
   back:"The Nazis destroyed the independence of the law:\n\n• Judges had to join the National Socialist League for the Maintenance of the Law and swear loyalty to Hitler.\n• Judges were expected to interpret cases according to Nazi ideology rather than impartial justice.\n• The People's Court (Volksgerichtshof), set up in 1934, tried 'political' crimes such as treason, often handing down death sentences.\n• There was no genuine appeal against Nazi 'justice', and the Gestapo could imprison people in 'protective custody' without any trial at all.\n\nThe rule of law was replaced by the will of the Führer.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-4-4", islandId:"h11i-01-4", front:"How did Goebbels use censorship and the media to control opinion?",
   back:"Joseph Goebbels, Minister of Public Enlightenment and Propaganda, controlled all information:\n\n• Newspapers — editors were told what to print under the Editors' Law (1933); anti-Nazi papers were closed.\n• Radio — cheap 'People's Receivers' (Volksempfänger) put Nazi broadcasts in homes, cafes and factories; loudspeakers blared speeches in the streets.\n• Film — every cinema showed a newsreel glorifying Hitler before the main feature; Leni Riefenstahl's Triumph of the Will (1935) celebrated the Nuremberg Rally.\n• Censorship — books by Jews and opponents were burned in 1933; art, music and literature had to fit Nazi ideals.\n\nThe aim was to make Nazi ideas seem natural and opposition unthinkable.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-4-5", islandId:"h11i-01-4", front:"Why were the Nuremberg Rallies and the 1936 Berlin Olympics important to the Nazis?",
   back:"Both were spectacular propaganda showcases:\n\nThe Nuremberg Rallies:\n• Held annually, they gathered hundreds of thousands in mass marches, searchlight displays and torchlit parades.\n• They created an overwhelming sense of order, power and unity behind the Führer.\n\nThe 1936 Berlin Olympics:\n• The Nazis built a vast modern stadium to impress foreign visitors and present Germany as peaceful, efficient and successful.\n• Anti-Jewish signs were temporarily removed to disguise persecution.\n• Although the African-American athlete Jesse Owens won four gold medals, undermining the 'master race' myth, Germany still topped the medal table and the Games were a propaganda triumph.", difficulty:2, category:"application"}
);
