Object.assign(LESSONS, {
  "h11i-01-4": `<h2>Nazi Control: The Police State &amp; Propaganda</h2>
<p>The Nazis turned Germany into a <strong>totalitarian police state</strong> in which the regime sought control over every aspect of life. Control rested on two pillars: <strong>terror</strong>, enforced by the SS and Gestapo, and <strong>persuasion</strong>, directed by Goebbels's propaganda machine.</p>
<h3>The instruments of terror</h3>
<p>Heinrich Himmler's <strong>SS</strong> ran the concentration camps and enforced racial policy, while the <strong>Gestapo</strong> spied on the population and made arrests without trial. The first camp, <strong>Dachau</strong>, opened in 1933 for political prisoners. The courts lost their independence: judges swore loyalty to Hitler, and the <strong>People's Court</strong> tried 'political' crimes, often with death sentences. People could be held in 'protective custody' with no trial at all.</p>
<h3>Censorship and propaganda</h3>
<p>Joseph <strong>Goebbels</strong> controlled all media. Newspapers were censored, cheap <strong>People's Receivers</strong> broadcast Nazi messages into homes, and every cinema showed pro-Hitler newsreels. Books by Jews and opponents were burned in 1933. The <strong>Nuremberg Rallies</strong> staged dazzling displays of unity and power, and the <strong>1936 Berlin Olympics</strong> projected an image of a peaceful, modern Germany to the world.</p>
<h3>Worked example</h3>
<p><strong>Q: Explain two ways the Nazis used terror to control Germany. (8 marks)</strong></p>
<p>First, the <strong>Gestapo</strong> spread fear. As the secret police they could arrest anyone suspected of disloyalty without trial. Because they relied on denunciations, Germans never knew who might be informing, so most people censored their own behaviour.</p>
<p>Second, the <strong>concentration camps</strong> intimidated opponents. From 1933, camps like Dachau held political prisoners who faced forced labour and brutal treatment. The threat of being sent to a camp silenced potential resistance.</p>
<h3>Common mistake</h3>
<p>Students sometimes claim the death camps of the Holocaust existed in 1933. In the 1930s the camps were for detention and intimidation; the dedicated extermination camps only appeared from 1941–42. Keep the chronology precise.</p>`
});

