FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h11i-01-6 — Persecution & the Racial State
  {id:"h11fc-01-6-1", islandId:"h11i-01-6", front:"What was Nazi racial ideology and the idea of the 'master race'?",
   back:"Nazi ideology was built on pseudo-scientific racism:\n\n• The Nazis claimed a so-called 'Aryan' master race (Herrenvolk), pictured as tall, blond and blue-eyed, was naturally superior.\n• Jewish people, Roma (Gypsies) and Slavs were labelled 'subhuman' (Untermenschen) and blamed for Germany's problems.\n• Antisemitism was central: Jews were falsely accused of betraying Germany in 1918 and of plotting to dominate the world.\n• The Nazis pursued eugenics — the idea of 'improving' the race by encouraging the 'fit' to breed and preventing the 'unfit', the disabled and the 'racially impure' from doing so.\n\nThis ideology justified escalating persecution and ultimately genocide.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-6-2", islandId:"h11i-01-6", front:"How did persecution of Jewish people escalate from 1933 to 1938?",
   back:"Persecution of Jews intensified step by step:\n\n• 1933 — a national boycott of Jewish shops and businesses (1 April); Jews barred from the civil service and many professions.\n• 1935 — the Nuremberg Laws: the Reich Citizenship Law stripped Jews of German citizenship, and the Law for the Protection of German Blood banned marriage and relationships between Jews and non-Jews.\n• 1938 — Kristallnacht (9–10 November): a state-organised pogrom in which synagogues, shops and homes were destroyed, around 100 Jews were killed and about 30,000 Jewish men were sent to concentration camps.\n\nEach stage isolated and dehumanised Jewish people further, paving the way for the Holocaust.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-6-3", islandId:"h11i-01-6", front:"What were the Nuremberg Laws of 1935?",
   back:"The Nuremberg Laws were two key racial laws announced in September 1935:\n\n• The Reich Citizenship Law — declared that only those of 'German blood' could be citizens, so Jews became mere 'subjects' with no political rights.\n• The Law for the Protection of German Blood and Honour — banned marriage and sexual relationships between Jews and non-Jewish Germans.\n\nLater decrees defined who counted as 'Jewish' based on grandparents' religion. The laws gave persecution a legal framework, formally separating Jews from German society and treating them as second-class outsiders.", difficulty:2, category:"definition"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-6-4", islandId:"h11i-01-6", front:"Which other groups did the Nazis persecute, and how?",
   back:"The racial state targeted many groups seen as 'undesirable':\n\n• Roma (Gypsies) — classed as racially inferior, registered, sterilised and later deported to camps and murdered.\n• Disabled people — the T4 'euthanasia' programme (from 1939) murdered around 70,000 mentally and physically disabled patients deemed 'unworthy of life', until protests (e.g. by Bishop von Galen) forced it underground.\n• People with hereditary illnesses — compulsorily sterilised under a 1933 law.\n• Political opponents — communists, socialists and trade unionists were among the first sent to concentration camps.\n• Homosexuals and Jehovah's Witnesses — imprisoned in camps.\n\nThe aim was a 'racially pure' national community.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},
  {id:"h11fc-01-6-5", islandId:"h11i-01-6", front:"How did Nazi policy move from ghettos to the Final Solution?",
   back:"After war began in 1939, persecution became mass murder:\n\n• Ghettos — in occupied Poland, Jews were forced into sealed, overcrowded ghettos (such as Warsaw) where many died of starvation and disease.\n• Einsatzgruppen — SS death squads following the 1941 invasion of the USSR shot hundreds of thousands of Jews and others.\n• The Wannsee Conference (January 1942) — Nazi leaders coordinated the 'Final Solution', the plan to murder all European Jews.\n• Death camps — Jews were transported to extermination camps such as Auschwitz-Birkenau, Treblinka and Sobibor and killed in gas chambers.\n\nAround six million Jews were murdered in this genocide, known as the Holocaust.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);
