Object.assign(LESSONS, {
  "h11i-01-6": `<h2>Persecution &amp; the Racial State</h2>
<p>At the heart of Nazi Germany lay a <strong>racial ideology</strong>. The Nazis claimed an 'Aryan' <strong>master race</strong> was superior and branded Jews, Roma and others as 'subhuman'. This pseudo-scientific racism justified persecution that escalated into genocide.</p>
<h3>The persecution of Jewish people</h3>
<p>Persecution intensified step by step. The <strong>1933 boycott</strong> targeted Jewish businesses; the <strong>Nuremberg Laws</strong> of 1935 stripped Jews of citizenship and banned marriage with non-Jews; and <strong>Kristallnacht</strong> in November 1938 saw a state-organised pogrom that destroyed synagogues and sent around 30,000 Jewish men to camps. Each stage isolated and dehumanised Jewish people further.</p>
<h3>Other victims and the road to genocide</h3>
<p>The racial state also targeted <strong>Roma</strong>, <strong>disabled people</strong> (the T4 'euthanasia' programme), people with hereditary illnesses, political opponents, homosexuals and Jehovah's Witnesses. After 1939, Jews in occupied Poland were forced into <strong>ghettos</strong>. The <strong>Wannsee Conference</strong> (1942) coordinated the <strong>Final Solution</strong>, and around six million Jews were murdered in death camps such as Auschwitz — the Holocaust.</p>
<h3>Worked example</h3>
<p><strong>Q: Explain why Nazi persecution of Jewish people increased between 1933 and 1942. (12 marks)</strong></p>
<p>One reason was <strong>ideology</strong>. Antisemitism was central to Nazism, so once in power the regime translated its hatred into law, beginning with boycotts and the Nuremberg Laws.</p>
<p>A second reason was the <strong>radicalising effect of war</strong>. The conquest of Poland and the USSR placed millions of Jews under Nazi control and removed restraints, allowing the move from ghettos and shootings to the systematic murder of the Final Solution from 1942.</p>
<h3>Common mistake</h3>
<p>Students sometimes assume the Holocaust was planned in detail from 1933. In fact policy escalated over time, from discrimination to emigration to ghettos and only then to mass murder. Showing this escalation gains higher marks than treating it as one fixed plan.</p>`
});
